        "Exclusive Shelf": "read",
        "My Review": "3.5 (rounded off to 3 because it is the year 2025 and Goodreads still does NOT have half star ratings)<br/><br/>This book is incredibly relevant in the current socio-political climate. One of the best done parts of this book explores Tess & Richard Welch; not only is the rallies and talks organised by Richard in the book directly inspired from the ongoing events but it also gives us this insight into not only what attracts attention and unwavering loyalty to these public figures but also the charisma & tactics employed by them to skirt the line of what is legal and illegal, inciting violence by words and overall drawing some important spotlight to the fact that words are just as bad as being the one to light the building on fire if they are unchecked. <br/><br/>I also enjoyed seeing Tess as this unwilling victim of becoming a spokesperson for the other side, having her own words controlled and set up as this beacon of worship, paralleling Richard Welch. <br/><br/>Ultimately what annoyed me is some of these plot points felt edgy for the shock factor (the parties) and a lot of the revelations came too late in the book - the Jack thread was promptly abandoned and picked right back up out of nowhere and I feel this book could have been an even more profound book if we had 1-2 threads we were following throughout vs trying to do a commentary on multiple things at once. <br/><br/>I would have also enjoyed a bit more characterisation with respect to our main character who mainly just acts as the eyes for us to view the events but we never learn enough for her to feel for her and what happens to her.<br/><br/>Would definitely recommend this book for anyone looking to understand the current political climate in USA.",
