        "Exclusive Shelf": "read",
        "My Review": "While I enjoyed the story and I enjoyed the conversation around capitalism and how it extracts work from you until it literally sucks you dry. This is driven further by how you’re doing the same thing over and over even when you are literally fevered. It was also a love letter to New York, or at least a letter to New York, how it has been taken away from the people who made it to serve those who work in shiny glass buildings and skyscrapers. There are ruminations about the experience of being an immigrant and how Candace is the way she is because her parents asked her to be useful and that is a uniquely immigrant experience/need  alongside the whole millennial thing <br/><br/>While I get all of that, I feel like the same were a little on the nose which is fine as long as there was something going on on the plot. Up until the end, we were following the plot very well (albeit being so dull) until we had an abrupt ending, which feels very weird for the reader because we’ve been following this character we’ve been watching her move through different landscapes and the ending doesn't provide closure of any sort. Everything doesn't need to be told, yes but a plot needs to move forward - you cannot choose a midpoint on it and deign it to be the ending. <br/><br/>This book felt like it desperately wanted to provide commentary trojan horse-d as a story - a lot of it is explained away because our main character goes through life thoroughly emotionally detached from her own body & surroundings. But reducing your side characters to caricatures with no real defining features, explaining away plot holes and introducing many moving parts cannot be completely explained just with her own characterisation. I feel this book could've benefited from honing in on 2/3 themes as opposed to including everything in a fairly short book that dragged the worldbuilding and character development down. ",
