        "Book Id": "61439040",
        "Title": "1984",
        "Author": "George Orwell",
        "Author l-f": "Orwell, George",
        "Additional Authors": "Thomas Pynchon",
        "ISBN": "=\"0452284236\"",
        "ISBN13": "=\"9780452284234\"",
        "My Rating": "5",
        "Average Rating": "4.20",
        "Publisher": "Plume",
        "Binding": "Paperback",
        "Number of Pages": "368",
        "Year Published": "2022",
        "Original Publication Year": "1949",
        "Date Read": "2025/08/17",
        "Date Added": "2025/07/03",
        "Bookshelves": "",
        "Bookshelves with positions": "",
        "Exclusive Shelf": "read",
        "My Review": "George Orwell is someone I’ve heard so many good things about but was always afraid to pick up something written by him due to the assumption that a classic is going to be difficult to read. When my book club picked this as the book of the month, I asked for six weeks to read it because I thought I was gonna log through it so imagine my surprise when I realised how readable this book is. due to the subject matter and what the book talks about, I really thought that it would be inaccessible when, in fact, I feel like the author made it accessible because of the demographic that most needs this.<br/><br/>1984 “imagines” a world where people are under constant surveillance and monitoring via the use of TV and print media is basically fiction that the government completely controls. The word is divided into three subcontinent who are constantly fighting, and the people in these three subcontinents live in the constant fear of war. The understanding is is that if everything can be monitored, there can be no internal attacks and you assume the government wants what’s best for you, so you give them privacy over your own thoughts until you are so propaganda-fed that you don’t know what your own thoughts are anymore.<br/><br/>[SPOILERS AHEAD - ANALYSIS OF TEXT FOR BOOK CLUB DISCUSSION] <br/><br/>Our main character works in one such faction of the government intended to rewrite history to ensure that all of what is going on is reflected in the past. The book starts from Winston, trying to write in the privacy or lack thereof in his home at writing desk, hidden from view of television on a diary, and we see our see our first glimpse of what’s wrong with this world - writing is no longer encouraged and instead, everything is dictated, making it much easier again to monitor people or what they’re saying. Similarly, English is simplified to \"newspeak\" to ensure words can only ever have one meaning and vocabulary is limited so words never make you think. Sex is reduced to an act done solely for procreation as your duty to the government/country but not necessarily something you'd approach outside of that - this is implied for two reasons: they want their citizens to be miserable; all that frustration can be channeled into projecting the same onto something else but also because physical intimacy implies freedom to express and to love - fundamental human experiences that the party doesn't want you to have because that is just a road away from realising the debilitating fuckedupness of your own situation. You are not allowed time away to be on your own - you go from work to communal recreational activity to home only for sleep and repeat; individualism invites space for reflection/thoughts. <br/><br/>Class plays an important role here as well - most of these things are only applicable to the party officials while the monitoring on proletariats is less severe, mostly restricted to propaganda that justifies their poor living conditions. People believed to be \"smart\" are often made an official, purely because it is easier to control them from the inside while proles are believed to be too ignorant to rebel - these freedoms are allowed for them as distractions to keep the content. Rewriting history helps because nothing can ever be proven otherwise making it difficult to incite reasonable doubt for a riot. <br/><br/><i> \"If both the past and the external world exist only in the mind and if the mind itself is controllable when then?\" </i> <br/><br/>In Part 2, Winston performs his singular act of rebellion by getting into a relationship with Julia - we seem them reclaim their own humanity and agency with this affair (I loved it for them). We also get some excellent commentary via Julia of apathetic activists who themselves are in a better off condition than the thing they're against - she is someone who only pushes back when directly affected. Orwell seems to use her to critique a certain kind of political apathy: the person who grumbles about injustice but doesn't engage in systemic resistance.<br/><br/>Winston believes that while the Party can control actions and thoughts outwardly, it can’t reach the core of a person’s self - their private feelings and loyalties. This line of thought is ultimately challenged and demolished presenting the ultimate truth - human spirit is not immovable when alone (hence the isolation during torture) and can be broken down until you're a shell of a person you were, looking onto your torturer as also your savior ultimately letting yourself be brainwashed. <br/><br/>While the monologue dedicated to breaking down the 3 slogans of the Party definitely dragged on and suspended into a full blown Orwell rant, the critique Orwell makes throughout of class structure and. power as a form of control is still relevant. In earlier times, inequality was explained as a necessary evil for the greater good. But in Oceania, the Party no longer pretends that inequality serves a higher purpose. <br/><br/>Big Brother is employed as a farce by the Party as sort of a mythical figure that inspires fear & loyalty, it is much easier to worship a singular person than an entire group of people behind it, this allows people to project onto him an image of who they want him to be (parasocial relationships). He becomes whatever the people want him to be to worship him.<br/><br/>We are also left debating if Winston in love with Julia - it feels like he knows things logically but doesn't feel them since he has eroded away all human emotions as a byproduct of working for the party. In Part 3, the downfall (& all hope I had for a revolution fades) as Winston faces torture. While not the ideal hero-saves-the-world story, this is the more realistic route since a singular person cannot overthrow a totalitarianism society - there can be no one hero. ",
