        "Exclusive Shelf": "dnf",
        "My Review": " I wanted to like this book more than anything else, and this DNF disappoints me. Gillian McAllister with her wrong, place wrong time, came at the best time for me as a reader who was tired of the basic, thriller storylines. However, with famous last words, the book did not live up to the premise. It actually started quite strong.  Part one was so incredibly fast-paced that I was rushing through the book to find out what happens next.<br/><br/>However, part two sucked out all of the momentum from the book. If you were to read part one part two a month apart, I don’t think you could tell that they from the same book. Part two takes place seven years post the hostage situation where Luke is now missing and we follow Camilla and Niall, both battling their own set of demons - we see Camilla on a date where she gets an anonymous text message and all she cares about is is that the fact that it might be Luke. I understand that this is a love story but there are very few women who do not have resentment and anchor harboured towards their partner, if they abandoned them with a newborn baby, and no parting words, and no explanation. This did not feel like a realistic depiction of that specially with the way that Camilla had been characterised so far. It rang so false where she sees Luke everywhere and she still so in love with Luke which she makes sure to tell every two sentences. Niall, on the other hand, was also suffering from night terrors, and his unresolved case, and his wife left him over that case, so like a typical detective backstory.<br/><br/>Around this point is when I stopped reading the story because I figured they would be some sort of absolution coming for Luke, some sort of explanation why he did what he did, or we have Camilla run away with Luke because it’s a love story and honestly none of the prospects sounded interesting to me. Especially with the pace at which the book was going, I could not soldier through it.",
