        "My Review": "3.5/3.75<br/><br/>This was an incredibly entertaining book, let’s get that out of the way. It took inspiration from the mysteries of yesteryear, most notably Agatha Christie and it delivered a product that was so incredibly unserious yet entertaining.<br/><br/>I have come to realise that with Riley Sagar, it’s always either hit or miss and sometimes even when it’s a hit, it’s really a miss, but I ignore it because his books are all so fast pacedso somethings always happening.<br/> <br/>The main character, Anna, is genuinely making the worst decisions at every single turn. She spends ALL her money on this train journey to gather all these criminals that have killed hundreds of people in the past, and she determined to let them all suffer with no concrete plan as to how and she is so surprised when one of these criminals does something egregious. Fork found in the kitchen much? What works here is that Anna is very much like an average person. She is not shown even in her past to have any deal capabilities that would differentiate her from other people, and we see her solely driven by sorrow, and urge to take revenge on these people that have ruined her life.<br/> <br/>The killer was so incredibly obvious from the get go. We knew who it was like you had to have known that if a character pops out out of nowhere in the book and is revealed to be the mysterious seventh person, and all of these murders are happening in between who do you think it is?<br/><br/>The way you approach this book is to just turn off your brain and have a good time because the instant you start thinking too much about everything and how things lineup so coincidentally you won’t have a good time. It’s completely unserious and I refuse to look at it any other way which contributed to the rating.<br/><br/>What did however bring the reading down is how terrible the writing is. I understand that you are taking a very cliche concept and you were trying to do something that honours it while bringing something to the table, but why did it read like Riley had roots in wattpad? there were so many instances where the book did not read like a book, but a parody of what they think a book should be like, and what a character should be feeling.<br/><br/><br/><br/>",
