        "Exclusive Shelf": "read",
        "My Review": "4.5 <br/><br/>This was a mystery/crime fiction unlike any I've ever read which is a tall claim. The timelines felt incredibly realistic and the investigation slogs on over months which feels very true to a police procedural. 1960s Japan is a timeframe I had no idea of but Matsumoto was able to paint a picture of it so thoroughly via Imanishi's travels - we start in the developing metropolitan city of Tokyo contrasted by rural areas in decline, cities like Osaka and Kyoto rebuilding themselves post war. <br/><br/>Matsumoto Seicho’s Inspector Imanishi Investigates is a page-turner which picks up around the 50% mark. The narrative switches between Imanishi's investigation alongside the young Yoshimura who are quickly closing in on the facts of the investigation and beginning to ask uncomfortable questions about the men that make up the Nouveau Group. The pace is fast and the complexity of the plot leavs you hanging for more. This is contrasted by glimpses of Imanishi's life aided by scenes from his home life (his wife is a saint), his special interests (bonsai and haiku) and lush descriptions of the places he sees during his official and unofficial trips.<br/><br/>This mystery was a perfect \"slice of life\" mystery for me in a way we don't see anymore - more often than not, all mysteries seem to increasingly be categorised into \"cozy\" or \"thrillers\". Inspector Imanishi Investigates steps outsides these genre confining boxes defining its own niche with a police procedural fit for an early 2000s detective show. <br/><br/>Matsumoto does an excellent job of misleading his readers and for once, I was totally fooled - I had fallen into the red herring he laid out. ",
