        "Bookshelves": "",
        "Bookshelves with positions": "",
        "Exclusive Shelf": "read",
        "My Review": "Just like my rating (3.5), I lie somewhere in the middle of all of the gushing and damning reviews this book has received.<br/><br/>It is incredibly important to acknowledge the meteoric rise of technological companies that aim to both influence user purchasing patterns, opinions and also sell the same to third parties for their own undisclosed use. The understanding of technology offered as a product is largely limited to \"allowing  users to connect and communicate\" or \"purchase goods\" but in the recent years, it has become clearer and clearer that data privacy is a bigger concern - nothing is truly erased off of the internet and we need to be more cognisant of the sites we engage with.  Everything we do is \"tracked\" to optimise engagement and have the product be \"addictive\" by nature. While that is a concerning pattern, we also need to acknowledge the other elephant in the room : lobbying. A lot of technological companies lobby governments for their own political reasons to forward their own business. At the end of the day, we are consumers and the apps we use are maximising profit, by hook or crook. Often times, such things are not obvious or transparent and we often forget about it, I know I do.<br/><br/>This book is incredibly important with respect to urging readers to acknowledge the reality we live in and the role technology plays in every aspect of our global proceedings right now. It is a call to be more aware as consumers and ultimately, highlights the lack of regulations and how much we still don't understand about technology especially with rapidly increasing technological advancements.<br/><br/>With that being said, the author is an incredibly frustrating narrator - the book suffers from lack of editing with chapters on & on drawling about the same points. In her early days at Facebook, she struggles with saying no and feels liberated when her husband helps her cope with the same but what she struggles with are inane requests ANYONE should be able to say no to. At the same time, it's difficult to ignore her own role in all of this - her work speaks less of one that does policymaking and more so seems to focus on building political relationships with governments around the world to ultimately \"sell\" Facebook as a service. That does not feel like policymaking to me. I respect her for the courage to throw her NDA in the water and reveal not only the external but internal decision making aspects of Facebook. However, Sarah never seems to realise she is also a Careless Person and just as complicit in the instances she reproaches her colleagues for - the only difference is she got out and chose to speak about it.<br/><br/>",
