        "Exclusive Shelf": "read",
        "My Review": "Remarkably Bright Creatures is a book that has been on my radar for a while - everyone around me seemed to love it but something about the cover dissuaded me. Goodreads has started a reading challenge where you collect bookmarks via fulfilling criteria for each of those bookmarks – I understand it for what it is but it's fun nonetheless and it prompted me to read this book.<br/><br/>My expectations and understanding about RBC was way off - I went in to this, thinking it's a plot-filled book with a mystery at its core (Eric somehow is alive was my best guess) and it completely flipped all of that on its head. <br/><br/><i> Very slight spoilers </i><br/>The book very quickly establishes a couple of things - <br/>1. Eric is very much dead.<br/>2. We follow two characters (Tova and Cameron) who live in completely different states with starkly different lives but it is consistently implied that their lives are tangled in some way.<br/>3. Marcellus can speak but he is also nearing his full age as an octopus.<br/><br/>In a way, there is no mystery to be discovered because the book presents most of its facts upfront and the rest of it feels very obvious but the charm is hidden, not in the plot (of which there is arguably little of) but the <i> vibes </i><br/><br/>Tova's sections were my favorite - her character has a lot more depth and being in her head established the setting so much better for me. Her lived experiences, emotions and thoughts felt so authentic to her character and her approach to life genuinely made me smile. I loved all the people she had in her life and the way they approached their friendships and relations to other people - it made me hopeful for an old age where I foster similar friendships. It was incredibly tender to read about and moved me to tears multiple times - her pain was very real and so was her happiness at all the obscure little things in her life. <br/><br/>When Janice said - \"That's your problem, assuming it's a burden\", it felt such a throwaway way of saying a lot in very little. Tova lives her life, isolated from others, afraid to let her guard down over the sorrow she still feels with the death of her son and husband. She presents herself as someone fiercely independent and steely but it's so reassuring to know that there are people who still look out for her, who don't consider her a burden and who go out of their way to \"trouble\" themselves for her.<br/><br/>Marcellus had me immediately captivated - he had astute observations about humans and like seemingly everyone else that read this book, I researched about Pacific Octopuses and became fascinated about all that the sea hides from us in plain sight. He was both funny and serious at the same time and his entire journey, though sparse, made my heart soar.<br/><br/>Cameron was meh - he was okay to read about and he definitely has a character development for the better in our book version of Stars Hollow but boy, was he insufferable and entitled at the big age of 30. He blamed everyone else for the way his life turned out, felt he was entitled to his dues despite so many having it so much worse and also the constant objectification of his to-be love interest felt really weird and out-of-place in the book tonally.<br/><br/>",
