        "Exclusive Shelf": "read",
        "My Review": "4.5<br/><br/>Okay, so truth be told, I always check the reviews first before writing a review for creative inspiration and mostly because I often forget the nitty gritty of what I read a month post reading it - this book seems to be super polarising, I saw so many extremes which, in hindsight, does not surprise me. <br/><br/>Thankfully, I had a great experience reading this - I often view romances with a side eye because more often than not, romances don't work out for xyz reasons but often, at least once in a year, I try to find a romance I genuinely love. This book was one that I approached with that mindset but it was so much more than just a romance - tagging it as a romance would be discounting what it did with the rest of its cast. I truly enjoyed the premise of it; that is a major reason I picked it up - I love Office Gossip and the idea of knowing everything everyone is saying was so satisfying<br/><br/> but I loved how feel-goody this was in terms of -<br/>1. Find out what everyone is saying about you.<br/>2. Get mad and convince yourself this reaffirms your own beliefs about everyone else.<br/>3. Come up with a plan to be better at your job because you can't afford to get laid off<br/>4. Shocker, you spend more time with your colleagues and learn they're real people.<br/><br/>I loved the relationships that Jolene forms with people in her team, the office idiosyncrasies and cheered Jolene for the plan she came up with at the big meeting and I especially loved her dynamic with Cliff. <br/><br/>I remember texting my boyfriend that the relationship between Cliff and Jolene was such a slowburn - they only kiss once and you feel so frustrated right alongside them but I enjoyed reading about two adults who acted like adults. Often times in romances even with a couple in their 30s, the text reads so unbelievable - they abandon all their responsibilities and slip into a life of just their partner (seven days in june, I am looking at you) while with this, the characters felt really grounded who were trying to address their attraction while still having an active life outside of it. I found Cliff a very fun character to read about; we don't spend too much time on how attractive he is and the author spends a lot of time fleshing out his personality and giving us enough time between Jolene and Cliff to feel the tension in how they interact + their compatibility. All of this made their relationship so much fun to read about. <br/><br/>I would say, I didn't care much for the arc with Armin - it felt too long and stretched on forever but I enjoyed the look it gave into Parsi families (very similar to desi families, who would've thought?)<br/>",
