        "Exclusive Shelf": "read",
        "My Review": "This was such an interesting short story - every single time I read a book from Kurt Vonnegut, I am struck by the impossibility of how accurately he imagined the modern landscape of a world he'd never live to see. <br/><br/>This story was a little odd in terms of the 14 year old and the empress he chose but overall, without delving into semantics and specifics, this acutely reminded me of the time 2 months ago when the ghibli trend from AI generated images took over the internet. Ethical implications of commodifying a painstakingly hand drawn franchise aside, a lot of people took to the internet to talk about how art deserves to be accessible and they deserve to be able to enjoy art and \"draw\" what they would like - the concepts in this story struck me oddly similar to that sentiment i.e. People should be equal regardless of whether they have put in the effort or not to build their expertise on that skill. Kurt Vonnegut had dreamed of a world where we would be provided impediments by the government to level the playing field - the world we live in achieves the same but by providing us enablers to move further ahead than we ordinarily would have. Why do we believe in our existence being of utmost importance that it entitles us to access things we've never worked for? \"Art should be accessible\" - tools to create art traditionally should be accessible but tools to generate art copying distinctive art styles of individuals who've spent years honing their craft shouldn't even exist, let alone be accessible.<br/><br/>I also love how clouded in mystery Harrison is - the entire book seems to be hinting at Harrison sort of saving the world and overthrowing the government to free people of the shackles that hold them back but Kurt turns this on its head by making Harrison just as bad of an evil who is ready to create a ruling class and establish a hierarchy for those who get to be freed of their impediments vs who don't which, while directly opposing egalitarianism, is still not the answer",
