        "Exclusive Shelf": "read",
        "My Review": "This very much fulfilled what it set out to do. As a thriller, Tell Me What You Did fulfilled exactly the highs of the genre.<br/><br/>The premise was honestly very unique to me. I love the idea of a podcast which typically involves mixed media this book managed incorporate to all of those elements very well. I especially loved the links of video recordings presented as evidence in between the book - that added another layer to it. The mystery in itself was very interesting -  at the core of this book what we are really exploring is whether the killer is who he says is. If you go one level deeper, it’s also about whether we should be taking matters into our own hands and what to do when the system fails you.<br/><br/><br/>With all of that being said is why I give this book 3 star rating because it managed to keep me engaged and rushing through the audiobook and the e-book in three days straight. I would’ve liked to see more of would be the momentum that we had in the first 30% of the book - that was incredibly fast paced and kept me at the edge of my seat honestly, but the more we got into the second half of the more things slowed down and honestly felt like they were repeating at some point - we were having largely the same conversations with different people and exploring different perspectives of what Poe had done from people in life. I would’ve also liked it if we had maybe explored a bit more about Hindley and about who he was just to freshen things up a little and not rehash over Poe’s life story so much. <br/><br/>Maybe an anonymous perspective of the killer where we don’t know whose perspective are we getting would have been fun and sort of contributed to the main theory - I feel at about 70% I was able to start putting things together which feels like a mystery well executed. Lastly, I loved that while Poe was drunk for most of the book, but we still didn’t have the unreliable narrator which is an overdone trope at this point",
