        "Bookshelves with positions": "",
        "Exclusive Shelf": "read",
        "My Review": "4.5 <br/><br/>this book was quite literally unputdownable. I started it off, thinking I would read 30 pages or so and go to sleep but I ended up reading the entire thing in one go. a testimony to the world that the author has created with the forever desert trilogy. My experience with the story of Osi was incredibly enjoyable - even moreso than the first one. Due to the established world, the author was able to pack this novella with a lot more plot and events in comparison to the first. The lore we do have in this book is all interspersed as part of the plot told in bits and pieces.<br/><br/>I enjoyed the callback to the story of Tutu and the way, the author crafted that story to transform with the upcoming generations, showing how histories often rewritten by those in power to support their own agendas, and cannot be trusted at face value. The people of the City of Truth have made the downfall of Tutu as the governing principle of their life, living in constant fear of the cult of the aleke - never once questioning the figure or how the increased taxes have not led to any more safety than before.<br/><br/>Moses is not afraid for his characters to be broken not just in spirit but also in body - this is particularly new for me in fiction wherein typical fantasies will have the main characters incur war with no real serious injuries or blemishes to their body. With the injuries that are character sustain, it increases the stakes a lot more and brings to reality the fact that at the ground level of every war are citizens who have been fed a doctrine from a very young age and sacrifice their lives while the ones in power sit comfortably watching it all unfold and having it all play out for them.<br/><br/><br/>The only place where the book fell flat for me, was the ending, which kind of came out of left field. I can understand the shock value that it brings to the book and how it turns the situation on the reader who think they can predict the ending. But due to the lack of any thing that would hint at it, it truly felt like it was only placed due to the shock value. My only redemption with the ending would be the fact that we know that the suppose bad guys are the ones who hold the truth & every war starts off with two sides, both of whom  think they are right. <br/><br/>Lastly, I enjoyed Osi as a character I enjoyed how he was and how he had a lot of growing up to do just like tutu -  he believed in a very idealistic view point of the world where things are right and wrong implicitly but sometimes that’s not the case, and he does go on to learn that the world does run in many shades of grey<br/> ",
