        "My Review": "4<br/><br/>Do yourself a favor and read this book. With a page count of under 100, 'The Lies of the Ajungo' took me by surprise with a masterclass in creating an intricate mystery, satisfying world building and a fable at its heart. It is in and of its own a feat to write a complete story within this page count and Moses Ose demonstrates the same so brilliantly in this novella - the author manages to pack in action, adventure and twists - truly displaying that you don't need a 350 page count for an immersive experience.<br/><br/>My expectation with this book was of a young boy going out into the desert, honing his skills, meeting friends along the way & the ultimate showdown with the root of evil ('Ajungo') bringing glory to his people and while all of that did happen, it materialised in an entirely unexpected manner. The core of this story lies in forcing the readers to question their biases, what we interpret when presented with a situation and ultimately how nothing is as it seems. <br/><br/>Every word in this book is so intentional, each character and their place in the story is so important inching Tutu and the reader to the truth with just the right amount of foreshadowing.<br/><br/>|| SPOILERS || <br/>If I were to analyse this book, in a way, the mechanisms employed here mirror the real world - promoting infighting between people, atrocities performed in the name of a greater evil that no one has ever seen & the clear class divide between the rich & the poor - it's not difficult to see the motivation behind the book. Our world today is not too different from the one in The Lies of the Ajungo - we go through our lives paying our own 'tax' in exchange for 'water' albeit the water itself may be meagre or just enough for us to not complain, we live in the shadows of the ones in power who makes these decisions on our behalf and we fight amongst ourselves to prevent unifying against real evil.",
