        "My Review": "revised rating to 4.5(1) <br/><br/>Fahrenheit 451 took me for a ride with its beginnings so disappointing I practically abandoned the book for 2ish months and only the flurry of the news in US right now + a youtube video motivated me to start it again. Luckily, the book turns around and honestly was a delightful reading experience. <br/><br/>I had the displeasure of learning Branbury's intentions when writing F451 - primarily written to boo critics who had pointed out the racist/sexist & xenophobic text in is prior book and believing the outrage was indicative of a future of censorship where nothing polarising could be written without it offending someone. <br/> <br/>I don't agree with Branbury's motivation and choose to view F451 in isolation of his own views because of how important the text is with respect to current times. I feel so strongly about the future he envisioned coming to life for the wrong reasons - we live in a time of depleted media literacy, a time where AI influencers are very rampant and ragebait is continually used as as a tool of capitalistic brands to farm engagement for their brands. We do live in a world where books are targeted by hostile governments - you cannot control a book or the intentions an author may communicate in his text and ultimately the personal interpretation the audience takes away from it and ultimately, we want to replace all of that with media that can be much more easily controlled.<br/><br/>This isn't just limited to book banning but the simplification/rampant summaries of books, we'd rather SparkNotes/ChatGPT our classics than actively engage with the material of our book. Popular influencers who've built their platforms on reading complain about having to read paragraphs. W<br/> Between the book-burning and discouragement of education and learning, we’re well on our way to creating a reality way too similar to the world of the book. F451 plays with a lot of themes - we often only associate censorship with the book however, themes explored in relation to social media (TV), the need for people to move on from one thing to another with no real reflection and how quick gratification ruins literacy/thinking is incredibly relevant on a more personal level across people.<br/><br/>Bradbury has a quote which encapsulates it best - censorship didn't affect the society, they stopped reading of their own accord (presumably moving to better mediums such as TV/summaries) <br/><br/>We are at as much of a danger from censorship from the government as we are to the dangers of falling prey to trends of brain rotting and doomscrolling, refusing to be intellectually challenged by the media we consume day in and out, boxing ourselves into our comfortable echo chambers with the sameness of our opinion everywhere. We are the danger to books as much as the looming threat of banned books.<br/>",
