        "Exclusive Shelf": "read",
        "My Review": "I once thought I knew the Mahabharat. In many ways, this book proved me wrong. <br/><br/>The book follows a river-like flow wherein initially it started off slow and confusing but like the story it tells, it crescendos into a high and creates an engaging narrative with themes many readers would be forced to think about.<br/><br/>This book forced me to think about my own position on the actions these characters took - Vaishnavi says it best when she says no one who was a part of Mahabharat was without faults and did misdeeds, it matters ultimately what the weight of those choices are. If you didn’t do what you had to do in those circumstances, what would have happened? Would that path be better than the one you are forced to take? <br/><br/>Every character was so profoundly complex - often times, I boil down this great epic that every Indian kid knows to the ‘good’ side Pandavs and the ‘bad’ side Kauravs but this book (and ultimately the Mahabharat) has provided so much background to these characters- are the good ones really good when they are presented with choices of gamble, misbehaviour, forgoing the rules of combat and acting as if they are beyond reproach? are the bad ones really so bad when you see instances of their humanity, empathy, bonds they’ve created, friendship and loyalty? ultimately you choose to abide by your belief of righteousness and you will always have people who don’t agree with you and what you do in these moments define you. The text was so deeply engaging in terms of dharma and adharma, conversations several characters have showed the multiple perspectives.<br/><br/>The exploration of bounding yourself to a belief, unwilling to change in the face of injustice to stand by your belief and how ultimately selfless intentions don’t always result in selfless actions was so beautiful and honestly, i know a retelling has done a good job when it makes me want to reread the original, Vaishnavi’s beautiful writing is always a plus (there are so many quotes i loved)",
