        "My Review": "3.5<br/><br/>The Girls I’ve Been takes up a concept I’ve never read before and turns into truly something worth listening 9h of audiobook of. It takes concepts of a bank heist and turns into something truly phenomenal because who could’ve guessed that the opportune day the robbers choose to rob the bank, there’s a con artist and an arsonist in the mix?<br/><br/>One of my gripes with media has always been showcasing fairly traumatic situations and characters bouncing back from it like it was nothing, however, here we toggle between the present and the past, a lot of which is traumatic and due justice is given to the characters in acknowledging the shitty situations they found themselves in and the effect it had on them and their lives. The plot is well-structured with little to no lulls/filler content in between which makes for an exciting read giving the story layers of complexity.<br/><br/>Where the book misses the mark, for me personally, is marking it as ‘Young Adult’ and having the characters be teenagers when the voice/tone of the story/characters felt very adult and it would’ve been more cohesive for them to be 21-23. The only reason I feel it was YA is purely for marketing reasons since YA is a lot more sellable than Adult. Similarly, shelving it as ‘Thriller’ does the book no favors because the stakes never felt high, it always felt like it was inching to a resolution that was a happy ending for the main cast and at no point, was I worried about the heist ending poorly for the trio.",
