        "My Review": "I feel like this is the work that I’ve been so confident is the book that deserves three star like this is a three star book. I loved the set up and the plot behind this book, however, would that being said the problem with this book is that it was always building up to something, but I feel like it never quite reached that. in part, the description does the book dirty because the description mentions the great grandson learning about Meher but we never quite see that happen in the book. <br/><br/>The dual POV does not do the story justice because there are so disconnected that it feels like you’re reading two completely different narratives with no parallels between them - in part. it happened because the author wanted to touch on a lot of different themes, but they were not really connected such as the patriarchy, oppression of women, the partition and racism faced by Indians abroad. <br/><br/>In addition to that, the great grandson’s narrative was just not interesting like it had nothing going for it except for a lot of exposition that ultimately led to no payoff - I like this book because it was a quick read and ma’s POV was incredibly interesting, specially in the glances where we get to see her home life and her married life, and getting used to a whole new way after living, a life of freedom. What me about the story however, is that we get no payoff again for what may end of being and what her story sums up to.",
