        "Bookshelves with positions": "",
        "Exclusive Shelf": "read",
        "My Review": "The premise sounded like something I could expect Tiktok POVs to have but to my pleasant surprise, Nikki Erlick used this premise to offer an empathetic look at how as situation like this upends the world on a global scale and more importantly, on an individual. <br/><br/>In the days since I've read this book, I have become an absolute menace to everyone positing 'what-if' questions about their strings and the people who'd live to face the consequences. The Measure provides a very humane look on people, love and relationships - it doesn't just hinge on 'short-stringers' but the people around them. The characters struggle to accept that their/their loved-ones' lives may end so soon - the dual approach that many people take is also interesting; people either leave their jobs, move away and travel to live their remaining years with no regret or they struggle to cope with the knowledge of a short life, their regrets mount and they use their short time to exact revenge on others or cause accidents on a wide scale. That's on an individual level but as for global, the story repeats as it has in the history of the world - as much as humans are united against the face of adversary, our textbooks prove that time and time again, humans find comfort in discrimination - in othering others to protect themselves - this reassures us that we are safe & inadvertently, better. While the commentary was a little on the nose, this book offered a fresh look at the discrimination that plagues our 'now', short-stringers used to forward political interests, fear-mongering of an experience the long-stringers don't understand, reduced opportunities (jobs, bank loans, promotions etc) - all speak of a world we are familiar with today.  The face of discrimination has changed, yes, but the discrimination remains there nonetheless.<br/><br/>While essentially general fiction guised as speculative sci-fi, it poised a lot of good questions -<br/>Would I open my box? If I knew I had little time left, would I continue living the way I was? Would I date a short-stringer? Marry them? Have children with them? Would I fake my results to ensure I am not discriminated against? <br/><br/>I would love to say I have all the answers but I don't.",
