        "My Review": "<i> How often are we bright stars in someone else’s sky, but they couldn’t find us with a fucking telescope, huh?  </i><br/><br/>The Villa is full to the brim with an idyllic setting at a villa I'd sure love to visit, two best friends reunited but with conflicting feelings and a murder that takes place in the 70s at the peak of rock n roll. A revealing story about womanhood, how easy it is to get lost in someone else, choosing yourself and paving your own path. Oh, and murder, of course. Overflowing with reveals that especially picked up at the very end, The Villa is not what it seems at first glance - you have your fleetwood mac-esque typical 70s rockstars and their hanger ons partying in a summer when things go very very wrong. The women these rockstars string along to hang onto their every word pave their own way finding themselves at the front of a career post murder and become famous in their right but is there something darker lingering beneath the clear cut murder sentence? The villa they stayed in has been inhabited several times since then but most notably finds itself at the brink of another murder half a century later when childhood best friends make their way to the villa for six weeks. Did I tell you they are writers desperately trying to get their next book out? That should make for a fun read and it did!<br/><br/>Rachel Hawkins nails the story capturing the vibes of the 70s so beautifully and alternatively making each timeline interesting slowly building the suspense. My only critique, akin to what I felt at The Wife Upstairs, would be that the pace is always so off - the books start off so slow at a snail's pace that I feel like I am drudging along only to pick up at the very end but good thing she does unique plots justice",
