        "My Review": "<i>“There is a difference between living the suffering and reading about it.” </i><br/><br/>A Magic Steeped in Poison is exactly what you would need when you crave comforting tea and a high-stakes show in the background. Interlaced with the competition in a bid to be the court's resident shennong-shi, the overarching mystery of the traitor within the court and the political intrigue in the book, the stakes are incredibly high in this book making for a read that eventually turns unputdownable. What really sold this book for me is the seamless weaving of mythology and use of ancient chinese practices forming the foundation of the magic system in the book. It's very important for the magic systems in books to be no longer reductive and explore + push boundaries as far as they can - safe to say, <i> a magic steeped in poison </i> has a beautiful, vivid and unique take on magic. Tea as a way to connect, soothe and heal is a love language so special to the global south where the very first thing we do when a weary loved-one comes back or a guest is at our house is offer them tea. It's more than just a drink, it's a way to form connections with the other persons - conversations held over warm tea have the power to invigorate you. A warm cup when drank alone in a bout of homesickness is enough to return you to the feeling of home for a moment and offer you peace. I love that the book really respected not only the art of making tea, a magic all on its own balanced on the ingredients you choose, but also the medium tea provides you when consumed with someone else to be able to link you with them. <br/><br/>The political intrigue was incredibly well done especially with Ning at the forefront of it all, dealing with two-faced individuals at every turn and not knowing who to trust beyond the barest of few who fell under the working class. The critique of capitalism and the concept of the 'rich frolicking by while the working class toils for them with no reprieve from taxes' was integrated very well and you can feel the sort of burden the blue-collared individuals live in this book. Ning was an a pleasure to read about; not only did she have the conviction to make the reader root her but she constantly made decisions that seemed to have an uniform line of thought. She was very strong in the face of danger but more importantly she was someone who was very skilled in her art and that made her just all the more interesting. Her loyalties were unwavering and I loved the way she defaulted to spending time in the kitchen feeling more at home there where everything was the way it seemed. Her internal conflict is very well fleshed out and I cannot wait to read about how she overcomes it in the coming book, forgiving herself for her past mistakes and moving forward with the knowledge she has now that she didn't then. Her relationship with Kang is still new - I am equal parts delighted and frustrated that Kang didn't have his own narrative focus beyond his time with Ning where we learn about his past because I like him and I want to read about him! But I get the choice the author made in choosing to keep us in the dark like Ning is, making their relationship believe because if I am enamored, I understand why she is!<br/><br/>ALSO NEED TO MENTION THE SAPPHIC PRINCESS X HANDMAIDEN? I need more.<br/><br/><br/>My main critiques are mainly the pacing which seemed to pick up at the end with a lot condensed into very little when that spread of plot over pages could have been more even. The descriptions were also very flowery and while exorbitant in nature, I couldn't imagine a lot of the places detailed, after which I began to skip them because the prose was not adding up with the vibe established like I cannot bring myself to care about the way the garden looks when someone is about to die.<br/><br/>",
