        "My Review": "<i> i know him, and in knowing him i love him, and in loving him i cannot do as he wishes </i><br/><br/>It is simply unfair that Alix has the power to say so much in so little because little did I know while going into a seemingly short story that it would play with my emotions so much. The Six Deaths of the Saint is beautifully tender in its portrayal of love and belonging - the writing is incredibly lyrical and only adds to the narrative prowess of the story. I did not expect that the story would as complex as it was with several twists taking me completely by surprise and the main character was stripped layer by layer revealing a little bit more about herself each time around. <br/><br/>Alix speaks of the desire to belong, to be somebody who's needed when they've spent their lives discarded, the price of power and blind devotion and how that can drive you to change your perception in your fierce need to be desired. A story about walls of delusion we build to lull us into a sense of safety and the blind eye we turn to maintain the reality we never had chasing the conditional love - how that often turns into a well of its own leaving us there entrapped in a place of our making and how connection with care for us and love us for who we are has the power to change all of that. And for all of this to be written by an author who so obviously cares about her characters and the way she tells her story makes for an incredibly reading experience.<br/><br/>Okay, I need to reread all my favorite scenes all over again",
