        "Exclusive Shelf": "read",
        "My Review": "<b> Read as part of BooksandLala Literally Dead Book Club </b> <br/><br/>House of Hunger was a book that really found its footing story-wise around 20% in which is the point I would say, I was completely invested in it and started having a lot of fun. Having read Year of the Witching and now House of Hunger, I can safely say Alexis Henderson will become a go-to for gothic historical fiction because I believe she is able to describe the surroundings so vividly and the central conflicts of her books are always interesting. House of Hunger is a gothic tale set in 1800s where rich nobles of the North often take up bloodmaids, usually from the poorer regions surrounding them including the South, where we follow a young girl, Marion, looking to escape her life of servitude and financial instability with the prospect of being a bloodmaid for Countess Lisavet for the House of Hunger where she makes new companions in the residing bloodmaids. Her fairytale life is ruined by the seemingly shady practices she notices that goes on at the House. <br/><br/>Marion was a very interesting character to me - not all her choices were smart but they made sense in the context of her situation where she lets herself be so enamored by Lisavet and turns a blind eye to the obvious for a while because you can tell, she wants to believe so badly that she can have this seemingly perfect life. I loved the clues Alexis has peppered in throughout the book about the main \"mystery\" and finding the threads to correlate them was so much fun as a reader. <br/><br/><spoiler> real talk the death of the house mother was probably more satisfying than lisavet like the house mother had no reason to be acting the way she was and she got what was coming to her </spoiler><br/><br/>Where House of Hunger faltered is the pacing. The first 10-15% (although it felt much longer) focused entirely on Marion's life before and her journey to becoming a bloodmaid in extensive details which was honestly quite slow and my reading experience would have been better if this was wrapped in 2/3 chapters as opposed to dedicating a good screen time of the book to this part which, ultimately, does nothing outlining her character beyond her resilience and desperation in escaping her circumstances. The part focused on Marion's introduction to the House, the bloodmaids and the Countess was very well-done but we again encountered issues when it came to the conflict and the calm before the storm. Marion's period of bliss with Lisavet was covered in one chapter and while you're ultimately not meant to root for this borderline Stockholm Syndrome relationship, I would have liked to see some degree of chemistry between the two - there was no clear understanding of why Marion was attracted to Lisavet beyond her beauty and the inherent gratitude Marion feels towards Lisavet for being pivotal in her escaping the North.  My main problem is the conflict/climax which is a part of the blurb and makes up for very little of the book - it is made to look like such a big part of the plot with the whole 'bloodmaids start disappearing' when that is clearly to mislead the reader and not enough attention was paid to fleshing out the cracks in Marion's fairytale - it just feels like she stumbled into the mystery. I also wished Alexis would commit to the mystery - the 'Wretch' written everywhere was overlooked, the mushroom mentioned in Lisavet's back story felt like it had a potential to tie back in a satisfying full circle way <br/><br/>Overall, I vastly prefer House of Hunger to Year of the Witching - the themes of power dynamics, exploitation of the poor, hunger, girlhood, what it means to choose when the stakes are off balance and the house as entity which quite literally feeds on you were very enjoyable against a compelling backdrop.",
