        "My Review": "3.5 <br/><br/>i am so sick and tired of authors building their story so lovingly with a main character you love and are invested in, sure, but more so, they build a hatred for a slew of characters/one character within the reader over the course of the book and the reader in all their assumptions edges closer towards the end hoping for a salvation to their hatred only for a mediocre ending and oh in case you forgot, the villain doesn't get the ending they deserve.<br/><br/><br/>i loved a lot of things about it, i did, which i will detail when i have time but let me talk about the negatives while it's still fresh in my mind :<br/><br/>i don't get why the witches were built to be evil, why did the finale have a big chunk of needing to defeat the witches - why couldn't they be morally grey but ultimately women who had been shunned to the forest, burnt at the pyre for \"sins\" that weren't upto them to begin with. i felt as if it were strongly implied that our fmc would find her safe space in these witches or their coven, learn their history and in turn their mom's and how the woods have become a safe for all those women who disappear into the forest after months of abuse at the hands of the men in a system that glorifies and encourages it. heck, i expected the woman running towards darkwoods during the blithe to be a statement of their liberation. the forest itself a metaphor for what they don't otherwise have. even when they said the forest doesn't take to the men well, i thought it rooted from the systemic injustic faced by women at the hands of men hence making the forest, a symbol and the body of the mother, untrusting of the witches as a whole. a lack of aligning reader expectations made this ~ twist ~ seem very out of left field.<br/><br/><br/>i don't get why immanuelle let the prophet go as if she hadn't murdered 4 witches just 5 pages ago, give them the same treatment?",
