        "My Review": "<b> 2.5 stars </b><br/><br/><br/>I am in Riley Sager's office, shaking him by the shoulders, asking him to be serious. I had such high hopes from Riley Sager, after having thoroughly enjoyed 3 of his past books only bypassing the 2021 thriller due to reviews that convinced me it was not for me, but this time, things were looking up. He had a Taylor Swift lyric in his epigraph and I was ready for tales of women scorned but obviously, given the rating, it disappointed. The first half was boring, maybe it's me but big chapters are such a turn-off, I was basically dredging my feet through it. Additionally, the drunk unreliable narrator trope is just no longer for me, I am not a fan of the common clichés employed within this trope such as 'everyone discredits the MC because they are drunk', 'MC questions their own memory and recollection of things because they are drunk', 'rain scene where MC is drunk', 'MC suspects everyone and pushes them away' like please please, put this trope to rest.<br/><br/><br/>*Spoilers Below*<br/><br/>The second part was even more exhausting than the first. The reveal of Katherine in Casey's house was great but it just went downhill from there, especially with how much suspension of disbelief it required. God, I was ready to settle for some half-assed story of Katherine and Eli having an affair hence leading Katherine to be aware of the whole Len arc and this being an eventual plot to frame Tom for some greater cause but no, Riley Sager, why? Why did you lean into the supernatural aspect of it all when you are a master at creating atmosphere? The atmosphere of House Across The Lake was nowhere spooky/creepy enough to warrant the use of this trope. I am so thoroughly disappointed, it feels like a copout and a bunch of tropes thrown together to form a story which is far less cohesive than any of his predecessors.",
