        "Bookshelves with positions": "",
        "Exclusive Shelf": "read",
        "My Review": "<b><i> \"Like the way friendship can be just as intense, beautiful and endless as romance. Like the way there's love everywhere around me - there's love for my friends, there's love for my paintings, there's love for myself,\" </i> </b><br/><br/>Despite my rating, this is one of my favorites of the year already. Do I have problems with it? Yes, but I've simply chosen to focus on the aspects I love and there is so so much to love. To see parts of myself in a book, thoughts I've had penned down word for word, was so validating. Like Georgia, I have never had romantic experiences to speak of and have often felt like I was behind my peers for never been able to jump into conversations with my own tales of sexual endeavours. I just feel so much love for this book - it's crazy. I love their friend group and the experiences they go through, which was handled realistically. No one in this book is perfect and it would be unrealistic to expect the same off of them because honestly, when you're 18, you are stepping into the world on your own for the first time and you will not get everything right. You are going to say hurtful things you don't mean, do things you regret in the future and find yourselves in situations that make you crawl into a ditch and you won't handle everything with the eloquence expected of you and that's okay. It was so fucking realistic and somehow, Alice Oseman made the slang in the book just perfect without making it seem like she was out of touch - some texts in this book could have literally been genuine conversations my friends and I have had. Georgia is, perhaps, the first character I have seen myself in - including the anxiety for making friends and socialising, spending all your time reading fanfiction and just desperately wanting to hold on to the friends you make, so much so that conflict scares you. <br/><br/><br/>Posting all quotes I loved because why not - <br/>\"I couldn't admit to them how desperately I wanted to be in a romantic relationship. Because I knew it was pathetic. Trust me. I completely understood that women should want to be strong and independent and you don't need to find love to have a successful life. And the fact that I so desperately wanted a boyfriend - or a girlfriend, a partner, whoever, someone - was a sign that I was not strong, or independent, or self-sufficient, or happy alone. I was really quite lonely, and I wanted to be loved.\" <br/><br/>\"God I just wanted to make a friend\" <br/><br/>\"Friends are automatically classed as 'less important' than romantic partners. I'd never questioned that. It was just the way the world was. I guess I'd always felt that friendship just couldn't compete with what a partner offered, and that I'd never really experience real love until I found romance.<br/>But if that had been true, I probably wouldn't have felt like this.\"<br/><br/>“I used to dream of a spellbinding, endless, forever romance. A beautiful story of meeting a person who could change your whole world.<br/><br/>But now, I realised, friendship could be that too.”<br/><br/>\"I hadn’t realised.<br/>I hadn’t realised how behind I was. I’d spent so much time thinking that my one true love would just show up one day. I had been wrong. I had been so, so wrong. Everyone else was growing up, kissing, having sex, falling in love, and I was just …<br/>I was just a child.<br/>And if I carried on like this … would I be alone forever?\"",
