        "My Review": "book rating - 4☆<br/>series rating (so far) - 3.5☆<br/><br/><b> what i like </b> -<br/>Tyson. He was so much fun to read about and he had a great arc so far. I am basically a sucker for big guys with big hearts.<br/><br/>Plot. I like how we're slowly drawing closer  to the battle that'll come in The Last Olympian. The twists in the last chapter were so so good - redemption arc for the whole book fr<br/><br/>Percy. As always, absolute golden boy. His development from being embarrassed for Tyson and invading Clarisse's quest to missing Tyson and putting himself in Clarrise's shoes. Best 13 year old ever.<br/><br/><br/><b> what i don't like </b> -<br/><br/>1.The growth of all the side characters - Since Percy is the main narrative voice in this novel a lot of it focuses on his emotions and how he feels about a particular situation which is great because a reader can feel for him and bond with him and be able to justify his actions, however in the same vein, you don't get the same sort of justification for any other character. For example  - I understand that Annabeth is sad but I don't feel the gravity of her emotions so I don't care about it all that much. A lot of it has to do with the fact that each book contains lots of adventures for a quest, making it harder to correctly display character intentions, important for growth, so when a character does something critical, it seems out of the blue.<br/><br/>2. How Greek mythologies are handled -  I love that this book was an avenue for kids who are fans of these mythologies to see the world represented in a way that it never had been before,however, this book also takes tropes of good and bad which I do not feel applied to the world of gods like poseidon is portrayed as a neutral character like he's good enough and most of his actions are justifiable in comparison to other. This book was also Hermes's redemption arc, and then people like Medusa Ares Circe who are portrayed as 'bad' gods. The Greek Gods are not as easily distinguishable as good and bad when most of them including Athena (who seems to be a favorite in the book) were in the grey and going ahead, I'd like that portrayed in the book, as percy's perception improves and matures with age. For example, the book is so biased towards Athena while Aphrodite is portrayed as shallow and it's just a very surface-level deep message to me, at least.",
