        "Exclusive Shelf": "read",
        "My Review": "this is one of my favorite books i've read this year and the one i'll probably credit in the years to come for reigniting my love for sff. <br/><br/>Iron widow is pitched as a reimagining of the lives of Wu Zeitan - China's only female emperor - against the backdrop of a world terrorized by strange aliens causing the government to develop giant transformer-like ships controlled by a male and female pilots by use of their qi. oh and the female pilot almost always dies in such endeavors and tragedy strikes Zeitan's family when her older sister dies in one such incident. Vowing to kill the man responsible for the death of her sister, Zeitan finds herself with more than what she bargained for, becoming entrenched in the mysteries of the oppressive system the government fights hard to keep secret.<br/><br/>Zeitan is an incredible protagonist and reading from her POV definitely made the story more enjoyable - she isn't the hero but the morally grey antihero, willing to sacrifice everything it takes to satisfy her own endgoals (as she should - let's go, girlboss!). She wants to destroy everything that she finds in this highly patriarchal world where the odds are stacked against her. Zeitan's anger was so prominent through the pages that I had my own teeth gritted, mentally screaming, \"Kill them all\"<br/><br/> I particularly enjoyed the emphasis on the continued pain in her feet - owing to the bounding ritual which took place when she was 5 - and am in awe of Xiran combined practices like foot binding in the futuristic world of Huaxia. Their depictions were incredibly moving and had me feeling phantom pain in my own feet.<br/><br/>The plot was incredibly engaging - I would be lying if it didn't take me a little getting into at the very start because the whole mechanics of the world were revealed, one layer at a time but as soon as she kills the male pilot, the plot picks up and never staggers even once. I finished the book in such a hurried frenzy, as if I couldn't stand to not know what happens next and if that doesn't tell you how good the book was, I don't know what will.<br/><br/>The poly M/F/M couple was not something I was privy to, prior picking up the novel but it was a great surprise and I love them all so much with all my heart - I only want more Shimin and Yizhi scenes, against the background of Yizhi's upbringing since I don't think we divulged enough into that. Additionally, I am curious of the lives of the side characters and hope that the author divulges further into their lives in a series of tidbits since the side characters have managed to strike a lasting impression on me.<br/><br/><br/>I would be lying if I said this book was perfect - it had its flaws but they were flaws I was okay with and I truly love this book for making me love SFF all over again. ",
