        "Exclusive Shelf": "read",
        "My Review": "This is a book one must reread with all the knowledge of the wars the Aristotle Mendoza holds inside him to appreciate it. For 70% of the book, I was reading it with no particular feelings bordering on either like or hate, however, the last 30% really made up for it. My biggest qualm about the book had been the lack of monologue from Aristotle about Dante which is why I was in constant disbelief of their friendship and consequently, love - however, the last half of the book serves to answer all of this and more. Aristotle is a beautiful character, carrying the ghost of his brother and his own conflicting feelings shrouded in loneliness inside him. His parents aren't without flaws - infact, they contribute to the person he is with how closed-off they've remained about Ari's brother, making it so as if he were dead leaving Ari to wonder who he was and why he haunts Ari's dreams. His father served the country during the Vietnam war, leaving him forever changed and he <i> can't </i> bring himself to talk about it and consequently, Ari has learnt to bottle things inside him allowing himself to feel anger at best, with no way to ask for help in the growing maze of puberty and his dreams. All of this changes when he meets Dante. Dante, who's so different from him and who has learnt to talk about his feelings. Dante who wears his heart on his sleeves. The book spans over the 2 summers prior to their senior as they grow up, finding companionship in each other amongst growing pains. They were adorable. I love them and I will be rereading if only to understand this book better. By the end of it, Ari's internal monologue was so much more fleshed out and complex, a hint of his own growth as he slowly learnt to come to terms with his feelings about everything . ",
