        "My Review": "Rereading harry potter was akin to dipping back into a river of nostalgia. Having grown up with the books and character for a better part of my life, reading book #1 felt like watching the movie in my head. It was every bit as good as I remembered it to be but with some exceptions - I can't digest the 'Chosen Boy' trope which is the very foundation of this book but the 'Chosen Boy can do no wrong' is insulting and annoying to Harry Potter - he's given so many passes just because he's <i> Potter </i> despite arguably, the real hero being the parents whose love outpowered Voldemort's hate. Harry and Draco are quite similar in ways except Harry is celebrated for it and Draco is not. Had these book been a 1st POV, it would make sense to be so favorable to Harry but it settles on a biased omnipresent narrator with clear loyalties towards some houses (much like Dumbledore). Another instance is the fact that everyone who's supposed to be 'evil'/'bad' is described as ugly which is such a simplified version of good vs evil to feed to children - sorry for expecting MG to be cleverer and not forgiving it for teaching what it does to impressionable audiences. However, with all these been said, did I still tear up when reading the part where Dumbledore awards the four with points and they get showered with love? Of course, I did.",
