        "Book Id": "57964185",
        "Title": "Project Hail Mary",
        "Author": "Andy Weir",
        "Author l-f": "Weir, Andy",
        "Additional Authors": "",
        "ISBN": "=\"059335527X\"",
        "ISBN13": "=\"9780593355275\"",
        "My Rating": "5",
        "Average Rating": "4.50",
        "Publisher": "Ballantine Books",
        "Binding": "Paperback",
        "Number of Pages": "478",
        "Year Published": "2021",
        "Original Publication Year": "2021",
        "Date Read": "2021/08/29",
        "Date Added": "2021/04/29",
        "Bookshelves": "favourites",
        "Bookshelves with positions": "favourites (#2)",
        "Exclusive Shelf": "read",
        "My Review": "<b> This review alludes to situations which occur in the later half of the book and hence, may be spoiler-y</b><br/><br/>Andy Weir does it again. Reading Project Hail Mary was an incredibly transformative experience - when I picked it a few days back, I expected the genius I've come to expect when Weir is involved, of course but what I didn't expect was to be sobbing at the friendship formed by Grace and Rocky. For a book that was marketed as sci-fi, this book made me cry 3 times (when Grace says \"Well, you're not alone anymore, buddy\", when Grace goes back to save Rocky sacrificing his chance at life on Earth and when the book ended)  <br/><br/>In a truer sense of the word, PHM is a thriller, an intense one at that - keeping the reader on the edge of their seats as conflicts come up with entirely believable baselines and you find yourself holding your breath, in how this may end. The stakes are so high that it's hard not to get emotionally invested in the characters - particularly when the French climatologist cried at what had to be done to offset the rate of extinction caused by Astrophage.  The world I live in has not yet experienced a mass extinction event, leading my own life to be one of unprecedented comfort, so placing myself in a familiar setting only with the looming danger of extinction was hard but Weir does it brilliantly with the chaotic nature of how Stratt leads the operation, pulled back into reality with mentions of how the government have settled with the way Stratt run things but aren't happy about it or how corporations still fight over petty things seemingly small in the face of an apocalypse. <br/><br/>When DuBois and Shapiro die, Weir's red herring about their relationship plays brilliantly - leading the reader to believe that the explosion may have been caused because they were busy fraternizing - is that part of human error? Sure but it places the responsibility of that on two people in love. However, Weir's intended plotline shows human error on a grander scale where the unit accidentally hands a milligram of Astrophage as opposed to a nanogram. To the average human, differences in this scale is so miniscule that it would barely go unnoticed but it brings into perspective the weighty danger of playing with fire (literally) and the consequences of the same or how they trudge forward knowing the lives lost but with no time to grieve. <br/><br/>This book particularly hinges on friendship and how the universal experience of life and loneliness seems to be present in communities from microbes all the way to intelligent species. Rocky and Grace were my favorite duo ever written - they carry so much sadness, guilt and responsibility over their actions (or lack therof) and how it led them to Tau Ceti but the way they find each other and rely on each other for support and companionship literally broke my heart. Like, I am not joking, there exists a weird spider dude in the Weir-Universe who makes me sob and laugh and I love him so much. My face leaks when I think of him, it's a human thing, understand? <br/><br/>Grace's dry humor is so (in)appropriately placed. Yes, the world is dying and he may be the only one able to save it but he's still full of quips and retorts, often using humor as a coping mechanism in the situations he finds himself in and to avoid facing his own shortcomings. His character development is so amazing - he finds himself on a ship, suffering from retrograde amnesia with his memory coming back in bouts. He soon realizes what the ship's original mission was and sets about to complete it on his own, despite how originally he was too scared to go on the mission and give up his life. It's funny what the brain can convince you and how much you can push yourself once you convince yourself you can. The moment when the plot finally reveals his act of cowardice, it's a far cry from the hero we've come to see Grace as - the man who does EVAs in 1.5g or the man who learnt the Eridian language in a matter of few weeks or the man who gave his crew members the appropriate see-off even when it was hard - and that moment truly cements Grace as a human. An amazing scientist, a brilliant microbiologist with a flair for invention but ultimately, a human who can't fathom willingly dying. This is in stark contrast to the Grace we see in Ch-27 who rides off back to Tau Ceti to save Rocky, knowing fully well he's directly walking towards his death when he has a chance at survival.  Their reunion is just so sweet. I love them so much. I can't deal. <br/><br/>This is all I have for now. Will I update when I think of more? Probably.",
