        "Exclusive Shelf": "read",
        "My Review": "For someone who has a bad track record with romances often ending up in dnfs, The Bromance Book Club was a pleasant surprise. <br/><br/>TBBC follows Gavin Scott on the brink of a divorce with his wife, serving as the wakeup call to the state their relationship is in. While desperately wanting to save his marriage, he reluctantly agrees to the help offered by his best friend, Del in the form of an undercover book club. The purpose of the book club, you ask? Men, in need of fixing their relationship and willing to go through growth, read romance novels to understand women's perspectives. <br/><br/>This book was an absolute delight to read and left a sappy smile on my face at all times. The main cast of characters are so endearing, in particular, the book club members who were the ones keeping the com angle of a rom-com alive her. I loved the way Gavin and Thea's relationship was laid out with conflict that felt real and stakes which seemed to affect the characters in drastic ways.<br/><br/>I loved the depth given to side characters, making them seem like real people which was done effectively without taking anything away from the main story.<br/><br/>All in all, men fighting for their family and going through self growth to put in the emotional growth required in a relationship with the help of their friends who let him have honest conversations, call him out in his bullshit and don't laugh at his shortcomings? why, yes, of course, that's a superior trope.<br/>",
        "Spoiler": "",
