        "My Review": "The year is 1955. Cyclists, street vendors and nimble-footed pedestrians bustle about the dusty roads of Jaipur. Amidst it all, huddled inside a tonga beside her faithful helper and a litany of tiffins, is thirty-year-old Lakshmi Shastri: the henna artist working for Jaipur’s elite complete with flashbacks detailing her failed marriage, her parents and the ayurvedic teachings of her mother-in-law. <br/>Lakshmi plays her role as the protagonist with grace, subverting expectations at every turn, navigating the landscapes of caste, class and patriarchal standards brimming under Jaipur’s luxurious pretences. On the other end of this spectrum is Radha, impatient, hard-headed and the kind of character one can’t help but roll their eyes at.Yet despite these traits, Radha shows moments of incredible strength and maturity, making it easy to forget that she is only a thirteen-year-old girl, and that like Lakshmi, she, too, has been a victim of society, circumstances, and the consequences of Lakshmi’s own actions from thirteen years ago.<br/><br/>In Alka Joshi’s debut novel, The Henna Artist, India is not just a country but an emotion embodied by the people who live there. At its core, this book is a tale of both individual and collective independence in a post-colonial India stuck between the richness of its culture and the allure of foreign trends. From distinguished ladies to battered servants, to hungry entrepreneurs like Lakshmi, this story is of women who dared to dream, to survive, and reach for a future beyond the bounds of their perceived station.  At times a coming-of-age story, at times family drama, much like Lakshmi’s designs, its intricacies are deftly wrapped within the folds of time, place, and a deceptively simple narrative. It is also a subtle critique of India’s ancient caste system and its intersections with latter-day capitalism; of cerebral and financial equality in a world where women cannot so much as walk the streets without a husband or chaperone in tow -- a thing that is, in many ways, not so far removed from present-day India.<br/><br/>Alka Joshi worked on The Henna Artist for a decade before it was picked up for publication. The heart and soul she put into this novel shows – a story of hope, ambition and healing.",
