        "My Review": "To its credit, Local Woman Missing has a very strong start. Delilah's POV is endearing and gritty, almost immediately making the reader root for her, holding their breath with her as she slinks away from her kidnappers and feel pure joy when it seems as if she's bought to justice. Part Two begins with the stormy night that took Meredith and Delilah away from Josh - we follow Meredith's neighbor, Kate who serves to bring the reader up to speed of the incidents that occur immediately after Meredith's disappearance. In addition, we have Meredith's POV, set a few months prior to her own disappearance, detailing her day to day life slowly inching the reader forward to the events that lead to the tragedy. Finally, we have Leo (Delilah's brother) as the side to explain all the events taking place in the \"now\", i.e., right after Delilah is found.<br/><br/>Despite the final \"villain\" being, more or less, predictable, this book was a page-turner with so many little twists going on at every corner and I couldn't seem to put it down, the thrill of finding the final puzzle piece keeping me at the edge of my seat. Additionally, the book delves into the lack of consent and general disregard of the mother's health during birth and post, where suspicions are chalked up to Meredith for having pills at her home from the time she had post-partum depression or Shelby's needs are neglected during birth with forceful pelvical exams despite her expressing discomfort. This book discusses these issues at length and let me question a practice which I, otherwise, wouldn't have.<br/><br/>With that being said, the book had too many red-herrings - a tactic which when employed perfectly can serve to misdirect the reader cleverly - however, in this case, none of the falsehoods had any sort of resolution leaving us with too many questions and no concrete answers (was the man following Bea and Meredith the OB/GYN or Jason? Who was the real father?)<br/><br/>Another problem was when details would be first mentioned serving the reader its intended purpose but would then be detailed at extensive length in another chapter with no actual payoff since the reader is already aware of how the situation ends.  This particularly struck me when a midwife tells Kate and Bea about Shelby's birth, leading to a possible lawsuit against the OB/GYN, which is then detailed in a much later chapter but why should I read it when the fate of the baby is already known to me? Dueling timelines can be hard to pull off but particularly, aligning details in a way that is consequential and of importance to the average reader. The book also had a lot of fluff, which ties into the very first point, lots of points are included for the sake of including them but serve no purpose to the actual story other than leaving the reader to mull it over on their own. We get extensive details of Meredith's home-life and her practice as doula, despite not much of it affecting the main story. There is a plotline where Leo is bullied by someone at the sitter's home and I still don't understand how that contributed in any matter towards building a narrative. Consequently, there's a part where Kate and Bea decide to be amateur sleuths and investigate the OB/GYN themselves which has no payoff other than immediate shock value. <br/><br/>I still don't understand why we didn't get Delilah's POV since she was a character the readers were rooting for but apart from Part One, we only see Delilah through the eyes of her brother when it could have been a POV plunged in confusion and constant questions. This is not a problem as such but Mary Kubica can't write male POVs - Leo came off as super \"pick me\" nice guy constantly lamenting about how doesn't have a girlfriend, like do I care? In similar vein, the writing had lots of <br/>telling the reader exactly what was going on, as opposed to show, which was so annoying because the author should at least trust their audience to be able to pick up on clues but instead, we get sentences like \"Today Bea turns 30. This is her birthday party. They are here to celebrate\" - this reads as if a bot was made to write prose. <br/><br/>Overall, this book was good for a quick read with lots of mindless twists and if you have a capacity for suspension of disbelief to the highest degree but look too closely at the plot and most of the narrative begins to fall apart to give something clearly implausible. ",
