        "Bookshelves": "",
        "Bookshelves with positions": "",
        "Exclusive Shelf": "read",
        "My Review": "<b> Slight spoilers ahead </b> <br/><br/>Upon initially finishing the book, my mind was set on this being a 4.5-stars - mainly because the climax of the plot was satisfying and every character got an arc that felt rightfully deserved. However, the more time I've had to process the character development and the plot itself, it bought the book down to a 2.5-stars.<br/><br/>The first half of the book seems to be in an infinite loop of Alison's mistakes, guilt and her toxic relationship with her husband. It is of no question that the author repeated the same scenario in different settings to emphasize the lack of both Alison's control over alcohol and the slow deterioration of her relationship with her husband. But it could have been done in so many ways. After a point, it was just the author reusing the same plot that she had typed for a good chunk of the book. With no character development to be seen in sight, it felt more like a \"Oh shit, here we go again\". <br/><br/>The synopsis sells itself as a struggling alcoholic whose anchor of hope turns out to be a client suspected of stabbing her husband.  The book doesn't delve further into the murder, having taken a sideline when compared to the car-wreck that is Alison's life.<br/><br/>To top it all off, the threatening texts Alison receives only deters her for a chapter or two, where she decides that she will be more present in her daughter's life only for her to go back to Patrick and repeat her mistakes on a grander scale than before. <br/><br/>The reader is led to believe that her life is moving in a positive upward trajectory (so much so you can almost forget how terrible Carl is) only for it to be a red herring.  <br/><br/>To the book's credit, the last 70 pages made up for the mess in the first half. Each chapter bought forth surprising revelations that alter every character's lives significantly and brings closure to several subplots. The multitude of smaller dramas along the way left me with disbelief at being misled by them.<br/><br/>Overall, there was a huge disjoint in my perception of what the book would be as opposed to what it was. The synopsis painted it as a story containing three over-arching subplots, however, only one of them was fleshed out properly, leading to slippery, poorly framed plots for the other two.<br/><br/>P.S. - were we supposed to believe Alison is good at her job? It was explicitly told to the reader quite a few times, however, just as the rule of \"show, don't tell\" goes, there was no evidence to back it up.",
